The paper deals with analyzing coverage properties in dynamic sensor networks, which involves studying the communication graph at each time point and tracking coverage holes in the network. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) or Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. However, the paper also uses computational topology and persistent homology to analyze the network, which suggests that it could belong to the Computational Geometry (cs.CG) or Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. Finally, the paper proposes a method for quantifying coverage using a weighted barcode, which suggests that it could also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Overall, cs.DS is the most likely sub-category as the paper deals with analyzing dynamic sensor networks, followed by cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.CG, and cs.IT.
